  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "Which of the following acid strength is used to get good yield of alkyl iodide from alcohol and sodium iodide in phosphoric acid?\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$15 \\%$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$35 \\%$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$65 \\%$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$95 \\%$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "\n<p><p>To convert an alcohol (R–OH) into an alkyl iodide (R–I) using NaI, the reaction proceeds by in situ generation of HI:  </p>\n<p>$$\\text{H}_3\\text{PO}_4 + \\text{NaI} \\longrightarrow \\text{NaH}_2\\text{PO}_4 + \\text{HI}$$  </p></p>\n\n<p><p>The freshly formed HI then protonates the –OH group and substitutes it:  </p>\n<p>$$\\begin{aligned}     \\text{R–OH} + \\text{HI} &\\longrightarrow \\text{R–I} + \\text{H}_2\\text{O}     \\end{aligned}$$  </p></p>\n<p><p>Key point: to get a good yield of R–I, the concentration of phosphoric acid must be high enough to  </p>\n<p>a. Generate sufficient HI  </p>\n<p>b. Protonate the –OH efficiently  </p></p>\n<p><p>“Concentrated phosphoric acid” in the laboratory typically means around 85–90 % (commercially often ~85 %). Among the given options, 95 % is the only choice that represents a truly concentrated acid.  </p></p>\n\n<p>Answer: Option D (95 %)</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2024,
    "yearKey": "mht-cet-pcb-2024-22th-april-morning-shift",
    "difficulty": null
  }
